history.text: Hello.  Do you like war movies?
No, not really. I prefer conversational ones. This one in particular had very little conversation.
Yes, but that does not mean that it is not interesting.
It depends on suspense and music to make it intriguing
It certainly was visually impressive. Did you like it?
Yes, I did and I think you will too.
The critics have given it high ratings
Yes, I saw it already. It was a tad pretentious I thought. No wonder critics like it.
Pretentious?  In what way?
Just visually very artsy. I prefer things more down to earth.
Well, the type of cinematography might not appeal to everyone, but it is good to see a director takes some risks
Even if it is for the sake of being "artsy"
Variety flavours life, after all
True. One must see it in surround sound. It was an very audio-oriented too.
Which is to be expected for a movie without much dialogue, I guess
Good point.
So, as you see, it is not about being pretentious, but about using certain elements to compensate for the lack of others
Churchill makes an appearance. He's in another movie too.
Churchill?  The only Churchill I know of is Winston Churchill.
You mean a character, not an actor?
Yes. I mean its set in WWII. so Churchill makes an appearance as in he is referenced.
Ok.  I was wondering. lol
FDR seems to get left out of WWII dramas. It's like a Churchill show.
Well, it is set in Britain, so I guess he is likely to make an appearance
Yes, but I just meant WWII movies in general.
Not too many women in war flicks as well. I guess that's one reason they don't appeal to me.
Have you seen anything else from this director?

Based on my knowledge of history, the US only became a super power after WWII.  That is why FDR was not very prominent.  Also, 
the women were working in the factories while the guys were away.  However, I could be wrong.
I am not familiar with that director.  What other movies did he act in?

Yes. The US became a superpower as we know it now after WWII, but it was the most powerful nation prior. It just didn't exercise that power globally. Churchill begged FDR to enter WWII so that "the new world could save the old" in his words/
I don't know his other movies either. But the reviews on this one are so good that it makes sense to look into them.
As far as I am concerned, the citizens of the US seem to live in a microcosm and are oblivious to the outside world.  Thanks to globalisation and of course, social media, this is changing.
Well, they were at D-Day.
I am not criticising, just making an observation.
